%N A391005 Semiperfect primes: p is a semiperfect prime <=> p is prime and p + 1 is semiperfect.
%C A391005 Note on terminology: We adopt the shorthand 'semiperfect prime' to denote a prime whose successor is semiperfect. This term is not intended to imply that the prime p itself satisfies the semiperfect property, which is impossible for primes.
%C A391005 Semiperfect primes that can be represented as the sum of some subset of the divisors of p + 1 are A391003.
%p A391005 select(n -> isprime(n) and isA005835(n+1), [seq(2..444)]);
%t A391005 pseudoPerfectQ[n_] := Module[{divs = Most[Divisors[n]]}, MemberQ[Total/@Subsets[ divs, Length[ divs]], n]];Select[Prime[Range[70]],pseudoPerfectQ[#+1]&] (* _James C. McMahon_, Nov 26 2025 *)
